<span id="freeTextContainer5498535639906734487">Sadly, I am starting new year with DNF.<br/><br/>I had high hopes for this book(series) but I couldn&apos;t get into it at all. But it&apos;s Conn Iggulden so I pushed and pushed myself onward until I got stuck on page 99 and decided not to waste any more time on this book. Thanks goodness I had only copy from library instead of buying whole series box set as was my original plan.<br/><br/>It&apos;s tricky to write fiction about famous historical figures. After reading this novel, I can say that I prefer Bernard Cornwell&apos;s style </span>
  <span id="freeText5498535639906734487" style="display:none">Sadly, I am starting new year with DNF.<br /><br />I had high hopes for this book(series) but I couldn't get into it at all. But it's Conn Iggulden so I pushed and pushed myself onward until I got stuck on page 99 and decided not to waste any more time on this book. Thanks goodness I had only copy from library instead of buying whole series box set as was my original plan.<br /><br />It's tricky to write fiction about famous historical figures. After reading this novel, I can say that I prefer Bernard Cornwell's style - he uses completely fictional character's perspective to tell the story of someone famous. On the other hand, Mr. Iggulden writes straight from Julius Caesar's POV in this novel and sadly it felt like boring fanfiction to me. <br /><br />I definitely won't continue with this series but I still plan to read Iggulden's more popular work about Genghis Khan in the future.</span>
